As the acidity had significant influence on the fluorescence of nanomaterials, the effects of pH values on the PL intensity of the PNPs were examined. As shown in Fig. 5
                        , The PL intensity of the PNPs remained constant in the pH range from 4 to 8. When the pH was below 4 and over 8, the PL intensity of the PNPs increased, which was different from native BSA, whose emission intensity decreased as the pH changed from 4 to 12 [40]. Moreover, the emission peak of the PNPs exhibited blue shift as pH value increased from 9 to 12 and almost didn’t change when the pH value varied from 2 to 7 (Fig. 6
                        ), which were in contrast with the results reported by Chiband [40]. As for the CNP, the PL intensity increased slowly as the pH changed from 2 to 7 and decreased slowly as the pH changed from 8 to 13. When the pH was 7 (close to physiological conditions), the PL intensity was the highest. (Fig. S14) In addition, the relationship between PL intensity of the PNPs and pH under the acidic conditions (pH = 2–4) or alkaline conditions (pH = 8–12) were well fitted with a linear fitting (Fig. S5), indicating that the PL properties of the PNPs were tightly related to protonation and deprotonation. The effects of protonation and deprotonation could efficiently influence the electrostatic environment of the chromophore or the electron density of molecules [41], which would dramatically affect the PL properties of fluorescent chromophore and finally resulted in different PL properties of the PNPs. Then, we investigated the UV–vis absorption spectra of the PNPs under different pH and the results were fantastic. The absorption spectra of the PNPs under pH from 2 to 10 were the same and the absorption peak at 275 nm gradually disappeared and shifted to long wavelength as the pH continued to increase (Fig. 7
                        ). These results demonstrated that the electronic transition of aromatic amino acids was greatly influenced under a strong alkaline condition, which agreed well with the results of PL spectra of the PNPs. It was worth noting that the molar absorbance at 330 nm (the maximum excitation wavelength of PNPs) didn’t change during the variation of pH (Fig. 7), indicating that it was the quantum yield of PNPs rather than molar absorbance that changed with pH [42]. Previous studies [38–40] reported that the fluorescence properties of BSA were associated with polar environment of tryptophan and the emission wavelength of BSA would undergo a red shift when the protein unfolding and exposure of the tryptophan occurred. In our work, the pH dependent fluorescence properties of the PNPs were entirely different with native BSA, further indicating the structure of the PNPs was transformed. All these results further indicated the PL of PNPs were derived from the conjugates that related to three kinds of aromatic amino acids.
